The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Sunday, December 21, 2003  Corporate Briefs																								 Micro Labs Ltd, a pharmaceutical firm, plans to invest Rs 100 crore in setting up three drug manufacturing units, two in Bangalore and one in Goa, next year. We are also exploring an option to start one unit in Himachal Pradesh, managing director Dilip Surana said. The Rs 450-crore company will merge its 11 divisions ahead of its initial public offer slated for next year.																								 Godrej has introduced home security products at the 17th Industrial India Trade Fair in Calcutta. In the locks segment, Godrej has added Godrej Twinbolt and Godrej Latchbolt varieties. These come with a hold back feature to avoid lock out situations and a deadlocking feature to prevent forced entry. Other security products on offer include Avanti, a security steel door, Private Eye, a video door phone, and Treasure Chest, an electronic digital safe.																								 Hewlett-Packard, Canon, Epson, Logitech and Intel have teamed up with MAIT, an apex IT body, to set up IT Anti-Counterfeit Coalition in the country. The coalition will work closely with the industry and the government by formulating strategies to curb counterfeiting of IT products in the country.																								 Strides Acrolab, an exporter of pharma products, has signed an agreement with Ribbon S. R. L. of Italy, a maker of semi-synthetic penicillins and cephalosporins, for a 50:50 joint venture company to manufacture and sell Cephalosporin formulations for the regulated markets. ADVERTISEMENT
